d. Conversely, gender-unfriendly countries have lower fertility rates than they would have if they changed their labor markets to encourage the hiring of women—and therein lies Japan's problem. The authors argue that the combination of an inhospitable labor market for women and insufficient support for childcare pushes women toward working harder to promote their careers, to the detriment of childbearing. Controversial and enlightening, this book provides policy recommendations for solving not just Japan's fertility issue but those of other modern democracies facing a similar crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aFertility, HumanzJapan. 0aWomenzJapanxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzJapanxSocial conditions. 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh1 aBoling, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinton, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstevez-Abe, Margarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirao, Keiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenjoh, Eiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenbluth, Frances McCall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenbluth, Frances McCall, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShirahase, Sawako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWada, Junichiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768207zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768207/original  aGBV-deGruyter-a